      <h3>Classic AeroPress recipes like a medium-fine starting point</h3>
      <p>For most everyday AeroPress brews, start around medium-fine. Think slightly finer than table salt, not powdery like store-bought espresso grind. That range usually gives you enough resistance to build sweetness without making the press feel like arm wrestling first thing in the morning.</p>

      <h3>Bypass brews usually want a touch finer</h3>
      <p>If you brew a short concentrate and then dilute with hot water, you can usually nudge the grinder a little finer. That gives the cup more punch before you stretch it out. Go too far, though, and the flavor gets harsh fast. AeroPress does not hide over-extraction very well.</p>

      <h3>Long steeps and darker roasts often want a little coarser</h3>
      <p>Darker coffee extracts quickly, and longer steep times do the same thing. Put both together with a too-fine grind and the cup can taste like bitter toast crust. If your press feels heavy and the finish dries your mouth out, back off a click or two before blaming the beans.</p>
    </section>
