  <Fragment slot="buying-guide">
    <BuyingGuideSection>
      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying guide: what actually matters in an AeroPress grinder</h2>

      <h3>Manual vs electric for AeroPress</h3>
      <p>If you brew one cup at a time, manual grinders make a lot of sense. They are smaller, usually give better grind quality per dollar, and pair naturally with how portable AeroPress already is. Electric grinders win when speed matters more than romance. If you brew before work or make coffee for two people, that convenience is not lazy. It is practical.</p>

      <h3>Grind range matters more than espresso bragging rights</h3>
      <p>A lot of grinders love to brag that they can do espresso. Fine. But AeroPress buyers should care more about a usable middle zone than a heroic ultra-fine range. The sweet spot is a grinder that can move cleanly through medium-fine to medium-coarse without feeling vague or jumpy.</p>

      <h3>Portability is not just size</h3>
      <p>A travel grinder should be small, yes, but it should also be low-mess and easy to reassemble without swearing at it in a hotel room. That is why compact body shape, catch-cup fit, and setting repeatability matter almost as much as raw burr quality for AeroPress travel kits.</p>

      <h3>When premium burr quality is worth paying for</h3>
      <p>Pay more when you brew AeroPress often enough to notice cup-to-cup drift, or when you like experimenting with recipes and want those changes to mean something. If you only make an occasional weekend mug, a value grinder is plenty. If AeroPress is your daily ritual, better consistency is not subtle. It shows up in sweeter cups and fewer frustrating misses.</p>

      <h3>Match the grinder to your real routine</h3>
      <p>If you want more help tuning the brew itself, check our <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-grind.html">AeroPress grind guide</a>, <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-grind-size.html">AeroPress grind size guide</a>, and <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-coffee-ratio.html">AeroPress coffee ratio guide</a>. If you are cross-shopping beyond AeroPress, our <a href="/posts/best-coffee-grinder-for-pour-over.html">best coffee grinder for pour over</a> and <a href="/posts/best-hand-grinder-for-espresso-under-100.html">best hand grinder for espresso under $100</a> guides help narrow the field fast.</p>
